<a name="9.1"></a>
<h2> 9.1 - Simple tips for linux users</h2>
d33 5
a37 5
There are several differences between OpenBSD and Linux. These
differences include but are not limited to, bootup
procedure, network interface usage and disk management. Most differences
are well documented, but involve searching manpages. This
document tries to be an index of those differences.<p>
d39 1
d41 38
a78 41
<li> OpenBSD has a ports tree. This is to accomodate the fact that at this
point not many applications are native to the OpenBSD environment. This is
both an attempt to get applications to work on OpenBSD for end-users and
to get more applications made with OpenBSD in mind. Eventually this ports
tree will be used to make a nice set of binary packages.
<li> OpenBSD uses CVS for source changes. Unlike Linux which is done
primarily thru seperate distributions, OpenBSD uses CVS which allows
anyone to extract the full source tree at ANY given time. OpenBSD also
does periodically release snapshots for various architectures and makes a
CD release every 6 months.
<li> OpenBSD contains STRONG CRYPTO, which USA based OS's cant contain.
(See <a href="../crypto.html">http://www.openbsd.org:/crypto.html</a>)
OpenBSD has also gone thru heavy security auditing and many security
features have already been impleminted into the source tree. (IPSEC,
KERBEROS).
<li>OpenBSD's kernel is /bsd.
<li>The names of hard disks are usually /dev/wd and /dev/sd (ATA/SCSI)
<li>/sbin/ifconfig with no arguments in linux gives the state of all the
interfaces. Under OpenBSD you need the -a flag.
<li>/sbin/route with no arguments in linux gives the state of all the
active routes. Under OpenBSD you need the "show" parameter, or do a netstat -r
(nice).
<li>IP-Masquerading is done trough ipnat. (<a
href="http://www.openbsd.org/cgi-bin/man.cgi?query=ipnat&apropos=0&sektion=1&format=html">ipnat(1)</a>)
<li>ipfwadm is done trough ipf (<a
href="http://www.openbsd.org/cgi-bin/man.cgi?query=ipf&apropos=0&sektion=1&format=html">ipf(1)</a>,
<a
href="http://www.openbsd.org/cgi-bin/man.cgi?query=ipnat&apropos=0&sektion=5&format=html">ipf(5)</a>)
<li>Interface address is stored on /etc/hostname.<interfacename>. It can
be a name
 instead of an IP address.
<li>The machine name is in /etc/myname
<li>The default gateway is in /etc/mygate
<li>The network interface aliases are in /etc/ifaliases
<li> OpenBSD's default shell is csh. Shells such as bash and tcsh can be
added as packages or installed from the ports tree.
<li>Password management changes a lot. The main files are different. (
<a
href="http://www.openbsd.org/cgi-bin/man.cgi?query=passwd&apropos=0&sektion=1&format=html">passwd(1)</a>,
<a
href="http://www.openbsd.org/cgi-bin/man.cgi?query=passwd&apropos=0&sektion=5&format=html">passwd(5)</a>)
d80 9
d90 3
a92 2
<a name="9.2"></a>
<h2> 9.2 - Dual booting Linux and OpenBSD</h2>
d94 3
a96 2
Yes! it is possible! <br>
Read <a href="INSTALL.linux">INSTALL.linux</a>
d98 6
d105 1
d107 5
a111 4
<a href=index.html><img height=24 width=24 src=../back.gif border=0
alt=OpenBSD$
<a href=mailto:www@@openbsd.org>www@@openbsd.org</a>
<br><small>$OpenBSD: faq9.html,v 1.3 1999/01/01 22:04:11 ericj Exp $</small>
a113 1

@


1.3
log
@few corrections
@
text
@d49 1
a49 1
href="http://www.openbsd.org/cgi-bin/man.cgi?query=ipnat&apropos=0&sektion=1&manpath=OpenBSD+2.4&format=html">ipnat(1)</a>)
d51 1
a51 1
href="http://www.openbsd.org/cgi-bin/man.cgi?query=ipf&apropos=0&sektion=1&manpath=OpenBSD+2.4&format=html">ipf(1)</a>,
d53 1
a53 1
href="http://www.openbsd.org/cgi-bin/man.cgi?query=ipnat&apropos=0&sektion=5&manpath=OpenBSD+2.4&format=html">ipf(5)</a>)
d64 1
a64 1
href="http://www.openbsd.org/cgi-bin/man.cgi?query=passwd&apropos=0&sektion=1&manpath=OpenBSD+2.4&format=html">passwd(1)</a>,
d66 1
a66 1
href="http://www.openbsd.org/cgi-bin/man.cgi?query=passwd&apropos=0&sektion=5&manpath=OpenBSD+2.4&format=html">passwd(5)</a>)
